# **Appendix A: Tenets (unless you know better ones)** {#appendix-a:-tenets-(unless-you-know-better-ones)}

1. **Security and operational performance**.  We put security and operational performance above all else.  
   * Status: Green  
2. **Accelerating ML adoption**.  We seek to solve the toughest problems holding back ML adoption, such as cost, ease of use, and data.  
   * Status: Green  
3. **Broadest and deepest selection**.  We seek to have the broadest and deepest selection of ML capabilities (frameworks and infrastructure, SageMaker services, AI API services and ML Solutions) that will make ML accessible to every developer, data scientist and business user.  
   * Status: Green  
4. **Long-term focus**.  We have a long-term focus.  It may take us a long time and heavy investment, but we will make AWS the best choice for ML services, AI services, ML-enabled applications, and ML-enabled devices.  
   * Status: Green  
5. **Broad customer definition**.  We seek to put machine learning in the hands of every developer, and we define “developer” broadly.  We cater to a broad set of customers, including developers with no ML expertise, developers who are on a path to become expert practitioners, data scientists, and researchers.  
   * Status: Green  
6. **Obsessed about customers**.  We are aware of competitors but we obsess only about customers. When faced with key decisions, we choose based on long-term customer value rather than on competitive concerns.  We are guided both by direct customer feedback and by our desire to solve the hardest and the most pressing problems of our times where AI can have the most transformative impact.  
   * Status: Green  
7. **Ethics and Public Policy**. We develop, operate and market our ML services in an ethical and legal manner. We actively engage in ethical, legal, regulatory and public policy discussions to help drive positive results for society as a whole.  Where others see problems, we see opportunities for helping customers with our services – to help them curate high-quality ground truth data, train highly accurate ML models that are free from implicit bias, and build applications that consider the perspectives of all stakeholders.  
   * Status: Green. We have engaged with customers, policymakers, regulators, and society groups around the world on the topic of responsible ML. We (the service team) invest heavily in core algorithmic research and development in bias and fairness, continuous evaluation of our services’ accuracy and fairness (or lack of bias), provide toolkits for our customers to build models that can address bias in their datasets and also be explainable (using tools like SageMaker Clarify), and are developing resources to help customers consider responsible use of our ML services. However, there is more work to do in engaging customers and policymakers on these issues, and we still see confusion around how to measure and consider ML accuracy and bias and how to responsibly build and use ML systems. We see increasing need for investment in Public Policy teams especially due to the need to proactively shape the active regulatory landscape so that our business can continue to grow to meet our customer needs and support their asks for increased investment in this area as it impacts not just ML business but wherever ML is used across AWS and Amazon.  
8. **Integration with AWS data services**.  We integrate heavily with our data, database and analytics services to make sure that our customers can easily leverage their own data on AWS to perform machine learning.   
   * Status: Green  
9. **Amazon itself as an inspirational customer**.  We view Amazon itself as an inspirational customer who can give us feedback and help us identify future services to build for the benefit of all customers.  
   * Status: Green. As noted in the main doc, if CDO was a paying customer they would be generating $458.6M ARR today (even after the CDO rate cards) through usage from Alexa, A9 search, Ads, Prime Photos, FCs, and Robotics. We expect our internal adoption will accelerate (2022 ARR of $1.3B from SageMaker, Rekognition, Transcribe, Translate, Monitron, and Polly) since internal teams are able to innovate faster and avoid investing hundreds of engineers and scientists by using our services. We are also building some unique capabilities such as M\* (our large NLP models equivalent to GPT-3) that will have non-linear impact for its search business in terms of ROI.  
10. **ML as a key ingredient for every AWS service**.  We partner with all AWS teams to help them integrate ML into their services to make them more intelligent. We believe that ML will be a key ingredient for every AWS service.  
    * Status: Green

# **Appendix C: 2022 FAQs** {#appendix-c:-2022-faqs}

1. ## **What are your disruptive ideas?** {#what-are-your-disruptive-ideas?}

Given the transformative potential of ML, more students and users learn ML than any other domain in computer science. Today, these users are not learning on AWS services, but *Seychelles* will change that. Seychelles will be a new SageMaker capability that will provide a subset of SageMaker Studio without requiring any setup, and at (potentially) zero cost so that ML users can begin their journey on AWS. Similarly, we are launching *Canvas* to expand SageMaker’s access to data analysts and other non-technical personas through a no-code ML interface. We believe both Seychelles and Canvas can open significant new opportunities for AWS ML.

Disruptive computer vision ideas include *Barracuda,* a new feature for Textract which allows customers to provide a ‘query’ on the information they wish to extract from a document. Barracuda uses this query (e.g. ‘vendor name?’) to answer questions that may not be explicitly manifest in a document such as an invoice, but implied from the context (e.g. the name typically located at the top of an invoice). Second, *Tangelo* will enable Alexa Smart Home and Ring to leverage Rekognition for person, pet, and package detection. Tangelo will reduce costs for Amazon and enable Ring to build new features, giving them an opportunity to gain additional revenue streams with an added benefit of opening this capability to external AWS customers like Simplisafe and Abode.

*Vector Code Builder* (VCB) and *Vector Query Builder* (VQB) introduce ML powered capabilities to a new set of user personas – professional and mainstream developers who are not well versed with cloud constructs (for VCB) and business analysts, program managers (for VQB). We believe VCB’s ability to enable developers to get code samples by stating their intent in plain English can drastically improve the art of software development in the long run and drive more adoption to AWS in the long run. *Sapphire* is a new machine learning-powered IDE built on these services that improves developer productivity by reducing the time to build cloud-based applications by up to 60%. Sapphire’s powerful code builder generates automatic code snippet recommendations when the developer writes their code and code comments. For software testing, Sapphire automatically recommends unit test code that matches their implementation code. Developers can also get code recommendations by describing their specific unit tests in natural language. Additionally, Sapphire’s built-in ML-based code reviews help developers automatically detect any bugs, security issues, and deviations from best coding practices. 

Designing conversational interfaces (aka chatbots) from contact center call transcripts can be cumbersome, time-intensive, and error-prone process. To address this pain point we will launch *Genie,* which automatically parses call transcripts to create a foundational bot design. With Genie, customers can overcome the initial hurdle of getting started, and reduce bot design time by up to 90%. 

***M\*/M5***: Large language models like GPT-3 and BERT generate good predictions for a wide range of tasks using just a few labeled examples. While versatile, they often cannot meet the production accuracy bar on their own, their size of over 100B parameters makes their use uneconomical, and they are not designed to meet Amazon’s needs, often trained on data sources of questionable provenance.   
*M\** and *M5* are new internal offerings for AWS AI/ML language services and CDO respectively for generating large language models and semantic representations of Amazon-specific entities (e.g., ASINs, customers, sellers, and queries). They break Amazon’s dependence on publicly available, large language models from third-parties like Facebook, Google, and OpenAI. A key innovation of M\*/M5 is the development of novel training mechanisms that leverage data from across multiple languages, multiple data types, multiple tasks, and multiple applications, thus sharing statistical strength. With these innovations, M\*/M5 models and tools allow Amazon teams to create custom models that meet specific cost, accuracy, and latency goals with just a handful of labeled examples. For AWS AI/ML, this benefits all language-related services, such as Comprehend, Lex, Kendra, and even Vector and Personalize. M\*/M5 enable performance improvements for our deep-learning systems and language services (e.g., $1.8B/yr ROI across Search, Catalog, Alexa, and other partner teams), and reduce data acquisition cost (e.g., $10MM-$30MM/yr for AWS AI/ML language services and $5MM-$10MM/yr for Search).

Through *SecurityGuru* we are going to address CISOs who want to ensure code compliance policies related to security in their code.  *SecurityGuru*, an automated-reasoning and ML-powered security service, will automatically create tailored security policies and provide recommendations to improve an application’s overall security posture. This makes it easy for CISOs and security engineers to create, manage, and enforce security policies across their code repositories and open source dependencies.

In ML Education, *Esperanza* is a Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion-focused scholarship program that aims to educate 20k underrepresented minorities each year in machine learning, leveraging a student-focused DeepRacer League. Esperanza includes $1.5M in scholarships, AWS internship opportunities, and mentoring; we are also looking for external sponsors (e.g. large AWS customers and partners) to increase the total value of scholarships distributed.

*Stark* enables marketers to easily create highly targeted audience segments by combining their first party data with third party datasets in a privacy preserving manner through Bastion, and automatically activate them as ad campaigns through Amazon Ads DSP (Demand Side Platform) or a marketing channel of their choice (e.g. email, push notifications, etc.). For campaigns activated through the Amazon Ads DSP, Stark enables marketers to combine their user data with Amazon’s first party data to generate even higher quality audience segments, leading to better business outcomes, such as an increase in purchases, subscriptions and higher user retention.

Finally, driven by advances in AI & ML, enterprises are investing in technologies called Robotic Process Automation (RPA) to automate manual tasks and business processes. RPA is one of the fastest growing areas in enterprise software. IDC estimates that RPA will grow from $3.3B in 2021 to $7.9B in 2024\. Further, operating RPA for mission-critical enterprise processes in a reliable, fault tolerant and highly scalable manner has been challenging for incumbent RPA providers. *Hercules* will provide an AWS managed RPA service to address this customer need. We did not include Hercules in the main narrative since it is not included in our top down allocation, but we are working in parallel on detailing out our product plans for Hercules.

2. ## **What were your top misses and learnings?  What are you most disappointed about in your area (dirty laundry)?** {#what-were-your-top-misses-and-learnings?-what-are-you-most-disappointed-about-in-your-area-(dirty-laundry)?}

On SageMaker, our top learning was that data labeling is increasingly being handled by non-technical personas like program managers who do not have access to development teams to use tools like GroundTruth and hence customers are looking for a fully turnkey solution where SageMaker takes care of setting up the data labeling and ensuring quality of label output. We will address this through the launch of *Beacon* at re:Invent this year.

On Lex, while we delivered contact center features such as barge-in, wait & continue, and time-outs, yet we were not able to provide the speech recognition accuracy desired by enterprise customers such as Barclays and Change Healthcare. To improve ASR accuracy, we upgraded US/UK English models in Q2 2021 reducing transcription errors by 50%. We plan to launch ASR features such as custom vocabulary and runtime hints to capture proper nouns for English locales by Sep’21. Also, we will deliver robust accent support for English locales and auto adaptation of domain-specific language models by end of 2021\. Our goal in 2022 will be to expand these improvements to non-English locales.

We are also disappointed at the slow adoption of CodeGuru Reviewer, and found that pricing was a big barrier for adoption. On 4/6/21, we launched our new pricing structure where customers now pay a monthly fee driven by the size of their on-boarded repos. Several churned customers like DevFactory, Mark43 and ClassMethod have returned to using the service. We saw a 42% increase in paid customers and realized a marginal increase (78% vs 63% historically) in paid customer retention. In addition we are adding features like CI/CD support, and enhancing CodeGuru to address security defects to make the service more compelling.

We are also disappointed at the slow adoption of Forecast which was targeted at SW developers. However, we learned that many customers prefer to buy end-to-end demand planning solutions from ISVs. Thus, we are pivoting to delivering Forecast through Foxtrot (demand planning application for business users being built within AWS) and ISVs such as  Anaplan, Lightspeed, and Kibo. Commerce.

Our HealthAI services – Comprehend Medical and Transcribe Medical \- have faced adoption headwinds. For Comprehend Medical we need to close gaps in our ontology support by supporting SNOMED-CT, CPT and LOINC. Similarly, we need to address more specialities like oncology, radiology and pathology. We will support SNOMED-CT in 2021 and CPT and LOINC in Q1-Q2 2022\. We will add support for oncology in 2021, and radiology and pathology in Q1-Q2 2022\. For Transcribe Medical, we learned that most providers preferred to buy a turn-key solution that directly integrated with their existing clinical workflows instead of building it themselves using APIs.  Also, while AWS is well equipped to sell to developers, we did not have a good path for direct sales into healthcare providers. We are working on a revised strategy for Transcribe Medical with a recommendation to focus on the Telehealth opportunity through integrated offerings from Telehealth software (e.g. Zoom, Cerner) and service providers (e.g. Teladoc, Amazon Care).

3. ## **What “dogs not barking” worry you?** {#what-“dogs-not-barking”-worry-you?}

Customers looking to build ML models on SageMaker or their own DIY platforms on AWS typically face data challenges. Often, they do not have the necessary data to build and train their ML models. There is a gap where they would benefit from a data sourcing solution to complement our data labeling and model training offerings in SageMaker. Lack of access to high quality data can restrict the usage of ML by our customers. While we are not considering offering a data sourcing service now, we will continue to keep a close eye on this. 

For Kendra, Google and Microsoft have a strong footprint in the enterprise productivity space but they don’t have an effective semantic search offering for enterprises. However, Microsoft has announced a beta version of a semantic search service which could challenge Kendra’s unique Q\&A and semantic search capabilities. To mitigate the risk, we are capitalizing on the head start by addressing known gaps such as SSO support, and delivering new innovative features like tabular search and reading comprehension for AES.

In addition to AI services from cloud service providers like Google and Microsoft, we see increased competition from hungry startups and niche players, with large sales teams focused on selling “one” thing especially for services such as Transcribe, Rekognition, Kendra, and SageMaker Ground Truth we also . For instance, with Transcribe we are facing compete pressure from startups like Otter.ai and Cresta.AI who are pushing to win workloads from customers like Zoom and Intuit (Cresta has gotten their foot in the door at Intuit already for an isolated use case). We are staying connected with our customers to address any feature gaps and training our field to focus on our differentiators. Separately, Microsoft has now gained a strong presence in contact centers through their acquisition of Nuance (at an enterprise valuation of $19.7B). Contact centers is the primary focus for services like Transcribe, Contact Lens, Lex, Polly, and Voice ID. While Nuance’s offerings fare poorly on accuracy, Microsoft could use their existing customer base to push their services more aggressively.

Today, ML models and solutions are built mostly by ML practitioners but over time we expect other personas like analysts to do more ML, yet products like SageMaker do not cater to non ML practitioners. Similarly, a lot of users are beginning to learn ML but they do not learn them on AWS services, and since tools are sticky, we run the risk of losing an emerging set of ML practitioners. We are addressing this in two ways. First for ML model building and deployment we are going to launch *Canvas* that is targeted at the non-technical persona while simultaneously continuing to improve the usability of SageMaker Studio. Second, we are launching *Seychelles* that will be a zero setup, easy to use ML environment at no charge so that we can get users to start their ML journey on AWS. On a related note we expect to see more customers who are looking for complete solutions rather than building blocks. To address this, we are launching more turnkey solutions like Kendra and Monitron that customers can deploy easily. Overall, we will need to continue these efforts and improve usability in a sustained way to expand to new personas. 

4. ## **What were your positive surprises over the last year?  How are you doubling down on them, and what are the specific actions and programs that evolved from these positive surprises?** {#what-were-your-positive-surprises-over-the-last-year?-how-are-you-doubling-down-on-them,-and-what-are-the-specific-actions-and-programs-that-evolved-from-these-positive-surprises?}

We are seeing strong growth in customers training large models (billions of parameters) and are doubling down on this by continuing to innovate on ML frameworks to provide the best training performance, working closely with the Trainium team to provide good HW acceleration and innovating on SageMaker features to provide training infrastructure optimizations like managed Spot, debuggers, profilers, and fast startup times. We also are seeing marquee customers like Fruitstand, Fannie Mae, Coinbase, JPMC, and Nike standardize on using SageMaker Studio and will double-down through better collaboration features and allowing developers to connect to Studio from IDEs running on their laptop. 

We’ve seen positive surprises across multiple language services. First, for Transcribe, we’re seeing strong customer adoption for the PII redaction feature and Custom Language Model (CLM) both of which are available as batch APIs. PII redaction helped us win workloads from Netflix and Intuit, while CLM makes it easy for businesses to adapt speech recognition to their company’s jargon and domain-specific language, such as at Octopus Energy, Allstate, and Echo 360\. We are doubling down on both these features by adding them to our streaming API later in 2021\. Second, customers are responding well to Custom Comprehend, an AutoML feature that enables them to upload their data and automatically build a model that understands their domain and facilitates identification of custom elements (e.g. nominee name in claim forms) or classification. This feature contributes to 60% of Comprehend revenue. To double down on customization, we will reduce the number of annotations required to train a custom model by 75% using data augmentation techniques and few-shot learning (Q1 2022). 

Among our Industrial initiatives, Monitron has seen large-scale adoption by Amazon Fulfillment Centers (FCs), with 152K sensors being deployed over the next 12 months across 100+ FCs in NA and EU. We are doubling down to meet the feature and scale requirements for this large order, and increase the deployment further with FCs in 2022 with an incremental 130K sensors. We are also drawing learnings from this engagement to shape our product (e.g., augmenting the ML experience) and GTM approach (e.g., defining the product adoption/sales lifecycle, case studies) for external customers.

In our Computer Vision services, we are seeing a large portion of revenue coming from startups; 31.4% of all Rekognition Q1 2021 charges came from startups, including companies like Honorlock (virtual proctoring use case), Verkada (security monitoring use case), and Samsara (face-based identification use case). Rekognition is the 2nd highest billed AI/ML Service by startups. Total Rekognition startup charges were $1.73M in Q1 2021, and monthly charges in March grew 88.4% YoY from $351.5K to $662.2K. We are exploring a startup-specific go-to-market campaign and service credit program to double down on Rekognition’s growth among startups.

For DeepRacer, we were surprised by the number of DeepRacer customers that a single enterprise can drive in a single year (DBS @3k, JPMC @2k, Accenture @1k). To double-down we’ve hired an SA to continue scaling our enterprise events through top AWS enterprise relationships. We’ve also been surprised by the increase in demand for DeepRacer in education, with almost half our events this year coming from schools or student-based organizations. We are doubling down here by first, partnering with AWS Academy and AWS Training & Certification to create ‘playbooks’ that educators can use to teach AIML with our products on a standalone basis or as integrations into their existing courses. Second we are partnering with AWS Educate to pilot an inter-collegiate DeepRacer competition in the Fall for roll-out globally in 2022\.

Spotting a critical gap in ML educational offerings, the Machine Learning Solutions Lab developed a business leader ML training program. The team realized that key to successful ML engagements is business executive support and buy-in, and that AWS could attain this through these training programs. These digital and instructor-led courses provide business leaders with foundational knowledge needed to recognize, evaluate and lead ML projects as well as begin shaping an ML strategy for their organizations.  In the 2.5 months since launch, the total digital enrollment is over 30,000 (against a 12 month goal of 24,000, \+127%), with a completion rate of 71.3% (against a 12 month completion rate goal of 75%).  We are pleased to see so much demand from business executives for our training, and believe this will help drive additional business and cement AWS’ reputation as a leader in AI.

11. ## **What are your top “paper cuts” and (where applicable), what are the worst tweets about your services? What are your plans to address the paper cuts, and if applicable, how have you reacted to the tweets? *Note: Where a paper cut is a small issue on its own, but taken in sum with other similar-sized issues, diminish the customer experience. Where we identify actions, need to also identify date for delivery.***  {#what-are-your-top-“paper-cuts”-and-(where-applicable),-what-are-the-worst-tweets-about-your-services?-what-are-your-plans-to-address-the-paper-cuts,-and-if-applicable,-how-have-you-reacted-to-the-tweets?-note:-where-a-paper-cut-is-a-small-issue-on-its-own,-but-taken-in-sum-with-other-similar-sized-issues,-diminish-the-customer-experience.-where-we-identify-actions,-need-to-also-identify-date-for-delivery.}

For SageMaker, top paper cuts include capacity challenges that require customers to think about instance availability in different regions and AZ’s, and requiring customers to submit requests for limit increases; both of these hinder our value prop of ‘managed infrastructure.’ Our startup latencies for creation of resources such as Training Jobs, Notebooks, and Endpoints is high (\~7 mins) and we are have several projects in progress to lower the startup latencies (under 2 minutes). 

For AI/ML services in air-gapped regions, the top paper cuts are associated with unclear C2S documentation and lack of service currency relative to commercial environments. For the first, we are working with the AWS documentation team to clarify and update the sample notebooks and diff docs by the end of Q3. For the second, we are reviewing stale pipelines in AI Ops meeting each week, with the goal of achieving \<60 day currency by the end of Q4.

*Here are the top paper cuts for our other AI Services:*

* For Transcribe, in order to add subtitles to their videos, media customers such as Discovery Communications and EEG Video go through an extra step to convert transcription output from a JSON file to an SRT or VTT file. To make this easier for customers, we will provide an option to directly generate SRT/VTT subtitle file as output from the service by Q3 2021\.   
* For Kendra, our top paper cut is the lack of fine tuning control in boosting certain field types, affecting customers like StatsPerform and Barclays. We are prioritizing this capability by 9/30.  
* Comprehend today supports tagging at a resource level only for its custom offerings. Customers such as SunLife, Amgen and McDonalds want to tag jobs for async workflows to a) track cost on a job by job basis for department wise cost allocation within the enterprise b) tag-based access management to ensure that users apply tags to their jobs, the right people can stop jobs.  We will launch job tagging to support these use cases (7/30).   
* For Translate, customers such as Refinitiv and Cyr3con with documents that are larger than 5KB use batch translation. However, batch translation has 10 mins start-up time adding latency. We will deliver sync-document translation to enable customers to get their documents translated using synchronous API (Q1 2022).  
* For Monitron, our top paper cuts are related to SSO. First is the log-in latency: it takes 30+ seconds for users to log into the Monitron app. This is the very first experience of Monitron and is a source of friction. The slow login experience is caused because AWS SSO is not optimized for mobile app authentication. The SSO team is investigating further**.** Second, SSO sessions expire every 8 hours forcing users to log into the Monitron app frequently. Customers have asked for a 1+ month session duration, with the option to configure so that they can set their own session length. SSO has a plan to increase the session length to a week in Q4 2021 but it does not fully meet the asks from our customers. Third, customers can’t trial Monitron without having to go through lengthy security approvals for SSO. AWS SSO is launching a capability called individual identity to address this issue (Q2 2022), and finally, customers can’t use Monitron in a region different from where their SSO is configured. This paper cut was tweeted by a customer. AWS SSO is working on cross-region data plane replication to address this issue (Q4 2021).  
* For Rekognition, our top paper cuts include two items: First, customers want to reject end-user submitted images where a face is not clearly visible. Today, Rekognition detects a face even when it is only partially visible. To mitigate this, we will add an occlusion attribute to all the faces APIs in 2022\. Second, an impediment to wide scale adoption of face-based authentication is that it is susceptible to spoofing as end-user pictures may be easily available in social media. In early 2022 we will launch liveness detection as a standalone Rekognition feature to make face compare and face search APIs spoof-free.  
* For DevOps, a key Reviewer paper cut is usability friction points for enterprise customers. That applies both to GitHub enterprise support and security detectors. Customers seem to struggle either adjusting to the required configurations or the required uploads to run the security detectors. We are solving this problem by introducing CI/CD support in late June 2021\. Having this integration in the common workflows that developers use every day will solve both problems. For the Profiler, the main struggle for our customers is handling flame graphs. They perceive the visualizations as complex and not intended for the common developer. We are planning on simplifying visualization and introducing new visuals that would appeal to the common developer by the end of Q4 2021\.

They are working on cross-region data plane replication (Q4 2021\) which will allow customers to use Monitron in a region that is different from where their AWS SSO is configured.

12. ## **Which of your security controls do your customers most commonly misconfigure?  What are you doing to address?** {#which-of-your-security-controls-do-your-customers-most-commonly-misconfigure? -what-are-you-doing-to-address?}

**SageMaker** (SM) offers a shared security model for their data (e.g. training data), code (e.g. algorithms, ML models), and infrastructure (e.g. training jobs, inference endpoints). Customers use AWS services such as VPC, Private Link, KMS, IAM, Tags, and Condition Keys to secure their ML resources in SageMaker. While DevOps engineers are more familiar with AWS security controls, this is relatively new for data scientitsts and they are more likely to misconfigure these settings. We are launching Seychelles at re:Invent’21 which will offer simplified and pre-built security controls for data scientists. The default SageMaker managed policy creates resources and enables access to underlying services such as S3 and CloudWatch in a single click to make it easy to get started. However, DevOps often find the default SageMaker managed policy not restrictive enough for their production environments and end up configuring custom policies, during which they can misconfigure the settings. We will continue improving our documentation and keeping the SageMaker Security Accelerator doc updated to highlight the recommended security best practices. 

Within the **Languages** business generally**,** configuring and managing IAM role policies takes non-trivial effort from customers. Any errors in this area can be detrimental to availability and/or security. For example, Transcribe expects customers to provide an IAM role that it can assume and write output transcripts to the customer-configured S3 bucket. Customers such as Verizon and JPMC had trouble configuring their IAM policies correctly, which prevented Transcribe from writing output to their S3 buckets. Some customers did not follow best practices such as configuring Key Management Service (KMS) encryption for their S3 buckets. To address these, we added support for Condition Keys in Transcribe APIs (Q4 2020). This allows account administrators to mandate/limit the S3 buckets and KMS keys that can be passed in the API requests. For L4E and Translate, we mitigated this concern by offering 1-click role creation in AWS console. 

For Kendra, Connector configuration tends to be where most of the security friction occurs. Customers store their repository credentials such as user-name/password for Sharepoint in AWS Secret Service. Data connector configuration contains IAM roles that Kendra use to access these credentials from Secret Service. Customers tend to misconfigure IAM role policies in the connector configuration as well as keying in repository access credentials. For 2022, we have prioritized overall connector improvements including AWS console UX in addition to 1-click role create that Kendra already offers to address these friction points. We are also prioritizing Service Linked Role (SLR) onboarding in 2022 to reduce friction around customer IAM policies.

13. ## **What do customers feel is not enterprise ready about your service and how are you addressing it in the next 12 to 18 months?** {#what-do-customers-feel-is-not-enterprise-ready-about-your-service-and-how-are-you-addressing-it-in-the-next-12-to-18-months?}

For ML frameworks and SageMaker, customers have not told us that any part of our service is not enterprise ready. Given the large scale production usage, this is not surprising. 

In the **Computer Vision** business, a few Textract customers (e.g. Refinitiv and ADP) brought up inconsistent and high async latency (PDF) as a blocker for using Textract. We are currently working on a new, faster PDF parser library and a new backend processing model that will allow customers to reason about latency, expected to be available Q3FY21. Additionally, for the face-based authentication use case, customers like Mercado Libre \- XXL, and Nubank \- XXL need to store a large number of faces (\~40M) as well as provide a near real-time response (P85 \< 3s) to the end-user. Today, Rekognition has a max limit of 20M faces per collection and provides high latency (mins to hours) when customers index and search a collection simultaneously. To retain existing customers and support other large customers, we will prioritize automated collection sharding, latency management, and allied tech-debt (e.g. change collection account & region) in 2022\.

Now looking to the **Languages** services, we plan to launch additional security, usability, and scalability features for Comprehend that will simplify integration, lower barrier to adoption, and reduce TCO for our enterprise customers. To address security needs of enterprise customers, in Mar 2021, we launched Customer Managed Key (CMK) encryption of custom models. We will extend VPC/KMS support for our Events and PII APIs (9/30). This is a key requirement for INT-B certification in the NatSec space, and has also been requested by Fannie Mae and Capital One. We will also launch cost allocation tagging for async jobs (9/30). For Kendra, customers such as Vanguard and Liberty Mutual have requested a solution that supports SSO and local groups in repositories such as Confluence and SharePoint. We plan to launch a solution for SSO and local group support for these repositories by 7/15.

For Lex, Enterprise customers such as Mutual Life Insurance and FRTIB expect to use AWS PrivateLink to access Amazon Lex from their VPC without requiring the traffic to traverse across internet. We plan to add AWS PrivateLink support Lex by 9/30. Like Lex, Forecast customers are looking for Private Link Integration to Forecast, which is on our Q4’21 roadmap. We are also looking to integrate with AppFlow to provide data transfer between Forecast and other data sources such as RedShift, Timestream, and ERP solutions (SAP) by Q4.

In the **ML-driven DevOps** space, AWS best practices are universally liked by customers, but the lack of end-to-end experiences reduce the utility of recommendations (e.g., build pipelines cannot be blocked when high severity security vulnerabilities are identified). Therefore we are integrating with popular CI/CD workflows (75+ PFRs \- GitHub alone has 5.6M Java developers and 8.4M Python developers) such as GitLab, GitHub Actions, Jenkins, and Code Pipelines. 

AWS-centric customers such as Fidelity and JPMC appreciate the automation of instrumentation and correlation capabilities of DevOps Guru, however, they (5 PFRs) want to see more features that allow them to customize or configure DevOps Guru to their specific needs. We will address this through Tagging, allowing them to control the presentation and notification of Insights through tag based filtering, sorting, and management. 

For Amazon HealthLake, we have prioritized initiatives in OP1 2021 to address Enterprise level FHIR Server capabilities.

Now looking to **Industrial AI services**, Panorama enterprise customers want to be able to perform remote troubleshooting on Panorama devices, bulk provision, and peform bulk fleet management; these are in our 2022 roadmap. For Lookout for Metrics (L4M), Enterprise customers want to be able to run anomaly detection on larger workloads than what L4M supports today. We have taken up an internal goal on scale and want to be able to support up to 1M time-series per detector (compared to 20K today).

Finally, within the Thought Leadership and Devices area, Enterprise organizations who are running large DeepRacer events want each of their employees to have a racer profile without having to sign up for an AWS account. AWS Identity does not support this use case, so we are shipping an approach of our own in June 2021 (until the AWS Identity team launches their solution sometime in 2022). Organizations also want the ability to see the participation status of individual employees in our courses and competitions.  In Q4, we will launch a new version of our event administration portal that enables org admins to assign any of our courses and/or competitions to their employees and view individual employee progress (% course completions, leaderboard standings).

With CodeGuru Reviewer, we see a big opportunity to innovate in the security space by making it easy for CISOs and security engineers to create, manage, and enforce security policies to detect vulnerabilities across their code repositories and opensource dependencies. We will expand upon our internal Dragonstone effort with an external service *SecurityGuru* to apply automated reasoning and machine learning to automatically create comprehensive and tailored security policies that proactively detect code security vulnerabilities such as injection flaws, broken authentication, or missing function level access control. 20. ## **New ML-added FAQ\! How are we addressing the need for growing ML education across students and industry?** {#new-ml-added-faq!-how-are-we-addressing-the-need-for-growing-ml-education-across-students-and-industry?}

ML training for Amazon and AWS customers is a critical success factor for us and our customers, and can be seen as driving thought leadership in practical ML by providing unique training to students and professionals. The AWS AIML team supports customers who want to learn ML through multiple channels: (1) Machine Learning University (MLU) produces educational courses for Amazonians and Machine Learning Solutions Lab customers via the AWS ML Embark program; (2) DeepRacer creates excitement through hands-on learning and friendly competition in racing leagues; (3) We partner with Coursera and Udacity to deliver ML content with breadth and topical coverage; and (4) Dive into Deep Learning (D2L) publishes an open source technical textbook that enables students, engineers, and scientists to understand and use DL via code, math, and discussions. Both D2L and MLU engage through courses taught at universities, lectures, talks, papers, internships, and grants. This year, DeepRacer is driving educational initiatives (like a student league and a DEI-focused scholarship program) to spur additional engagement with universities. Finally, Seychelles (launching at re:Invent 2021\) will provide a freely available and simple setup experience for SageMaker Studio-like capabilities which will enable us to deliver enhanced hands-on notebook experiences for DeepRacer, D2L, and other MLU offerings.

Additionally, our Machine Learning Solutions Lab developed a business leader training program to augment our technical leader training because one key to successful machine learning projects is business leader support and buy-in. Our digital and instructor-led training courses provides business leaders with foundational knowledge needed to recognize, evaluate and lead ML projects as well as begin shaping an ML strategy for their organizations. Lastly, Amazon SageMaker will launch Seychelles, a no charge, no setup ML development environment based on Studio for researchers and students. Seychelles will have capabilities for collaboration among users; users will be able to publish projects and leverage those of others. We will add gamification and community features such as ML competitions and leaderboards in Seychelles.

21. ## **New ML-added FAQ\! What are we doing to address fairness and bias in AI/ML?** {#new-ml-added-faq!-what-are-we-doing-to-address-fairness-and-bias-in-ai/ml?}

The AWS AI team aims to build and maintain services in accordance with standards of fairness that our customers and public expect and which make sense for our business. We do so by investing in research on algorithmic fairness, establishing mechanisms to ensure developers are thinking about bias issues at the start of the design process, sourcing diverse data, defining bias metrics and benchmarking our performance against these metrics. We also provide toolkits for our customers to build models that can address bias in their datasets and also be explainable (using tools like SageMaker Clarify), and are developing resources to help customers consider responsible use of our ML services. On top of these efforts undertaken over the past years, just this year we formally established the Themis team as a way to conduct independent assessments of bias in our AI services and features, as well as providing additional resources to the service teams to help prevent and mitigate bias. Modelled after the AWS’s benchmarking team, the Themis team will: (1) measure and work with the service teams to prevent and mitigate bias for AWS’ top priority AI services and features (including sourcing Themis’ own test data sets); (2) extract common themes in evaluating, preventing and mitigating bias across multiple services to develop common solutions and even self-service tools for use by any Amazon team; (3) create and offer educational training (through MLU) for Amazon employees on how to detect, prevent and mitigate bias in AI systems, including developing a few case studies for purposes of illustration; and (4) conduct research in fairness and the related areas of explainability, robustness and privacy. In its first year, Themis considered 90 AWS AI features or services, prioritizing them for review, and by the end of 2021, will have reviewed 6 of the highest priority services/features. The team aims to do more with additional allocated headcount in 2022\. To our knowledge, no other company has a team like Themis with its mission, scope and independence. While impossible to predict and prevent all potential challenges to the fairness of AWS’ AI services, the above efforts take concrete, substantive steps toward systematically minimizing bias and provide enduring mechanisms towards enhancing the fairness in our AI services and help customers understand the issue of potential biases in their ML systems and build responsible AI solutions.

2. ## **What significant launches do you have planned over the next 18 months, and how do they impact the P\&L?**

AI/ML will continue to invest in SageMaker, including key 2021 re:Invent launches such as Seychelles, Liberty, Canvas, Beacon, and Axis, contributing $22M ARR in 2022 (5.4% of total SageMaker revenue).

Between Q1’22 and Q3’22, Rekognition plans to launch new features such as Liveness detection and Tangelo (live streaming analysis API for security monitoring use cases; Ring and Alexa Smart Home will be CDO customers for this API), in addition to improving the model quality of existing APIs such as faces, moderation, labels and custom labels, and text. (b) Use-Case Specific APIs that offer richer inferences with less custom post-processing for specialized high-value documents in loan processing (Pinstripe), invoices and receipts (AnalyzeExpense), as well as identity extraction (AnalyzeID). | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |

The AWS Central Econ team provided an update of AI/ML’s DSI analysis in Jul-21 and estimated total AI/ML’s weighted average DSI multiplier at 3.1 (vs. 3.3 in last year’s DSI analysis), based on individual DSI by service as shown in the table above. This means that for every $1 spent per month on AI/ML, customers spend $3.1 dollar on other AWS services (mostly from Compute, Database, and Analytics services). These multipliers refer to the first few months’ post ML adoption and capture spend by customers that occurred because they adopted an ML service, that is, spend that is above and beyond what they would have spent on AWS had they not adopted the ML service. 

We further estimate the associated DSI contribution profit by applying overall AWS’s contribution margin of 46% based on 2021 OP2 plan. For example, AI/ML 2026 revenue is forecasted at $6.1B with contribution profit of $3.3B. With DSI revenue of $19.0B ($6.1B \*3.1) and DSI contribution profit of $8.7B (DSI revenue of $19.0B \* AWS CM% of 46%), total AI/ML revenue inclusive of DSI would be $25.1B ($6.1B \+ $19.0B) with contribution profit of $12.0B ($3.3B \+ $8.7B) in 2026\.  To calculate DSI operating profit, we reduce DSI contribution profit by fixed costs based on 17% of revenue (2021 OP2 plan).  Based on the methodology above, all-in AI/ML net profit inclusive of DSI would be $5.3B (vs. $1.2B without DSI) by 2026\.

9. ## **What is ML Thought Leadership product and why does it have negative revenue growth with negative CM% in the long run?** 

The ML Thought Leadership business develops projects such as DeepLens and DeepComposer, whose goal is to use a fixed-cost investment (12 Flat HC) to drive perception and awareness of AWS’s prowess in AI/ML through hands-on ML education. The team’s charter is to develop new experiments on a regular basis with the expectation that if any gain traction, we spin them off and track their P\&L separately (e.g. DeepRacer). Therefore this business will never show positive revenue growth, and we contain our cost exposure by maintaining a fixed headcount.

ML Thought Leadership contribution margin (CM%) is expected to be negative with the current strategy mentioned above, as we plan to sell with deep discounts to attract more customers to maximize marketing impact. At the same time, it will allow us to sell off our inventory for DeepLens and DeepComposer (we stopped manufacturing both products in 2019).

10. ## **Why do Deep Racer, Personalize, A2I and Asimov have low net margin (NM%) below 10% by 2026?**

DeepRacer standalone is not expected to be NM% breakeven without DSI. DeepRacer is positioned to encourage new people to get involved with AWS technology by investing in programs like DeepRacer League and Esperanza. While the team works on cost reduction (target to increase infra margin by \+50pts in 2021), we continue to bring the benefits back to the community by launching meaningful new programs and offering better price to customers (plan to reduce net ASP from $3.0/hour to $2.0/hour by 2026). With our DSI analysis (4.6x multiplier provided by DeepRacer team, pending for Econ team’s review and confirmation), we expect DeepRacer to reach NM% breakeven in 2024 and improve it to 5% by 2026 (vs. \-68% NM w/o DSI).

A2I reaches NM% breakeven in 2026 at 2%, mainly due to a strategic shift in focus from A2I to Beacon, a new feature of SageMaker GroundTruth. Beacon in a turnkey solution for data annotation and human in the loop needs for AI/ML. As a result, A2I is entering keep the lights on (KTLO) as of 2023, where we expect modest YoY growth, with limited HC. As a result, we expect A2I to maintain low, but positive net margins. 

Asimov’s NM% is \-61% in 2021 and would be improved to \-20% by 2026\. Asimov provides deep learning AMIs (DLAMI) and containers (DLC) that SageMaker, EC2, ECS, and EKS customers use to run AWS-optimized ML frameworks on their infrastructure. Asimov also delivers framework-integrated libraries for large-scale model training on distributed systems to XXL customers such as Facebook and Bloomberg. Deep Learning training workloads on EC2 Accelerated Compute instances account for \~$680M ARR and on SageMaker account for at least $12M ARR. Asimov P\&L has a low NM% because it tracks only the fraction of the deep learning workloads that can be associated with known AMI IDs (outside a VPC) but carries the infrastructure cost and headcount that enable all deep learning workloads that are monetized by EC2, EKS, ECS, and SageMaker. Asimov uses the headcount and infrastructure to optimize ML frameworks for AWS, tune and test customer-representative models, and present benchmarks that showcase the best performance and price for models such as Mask R-CNN, BERT, and GPT-3 on AWS. The technical leadership shown in the benchmarks presented at re:Invent 2020 brought customers such as Facebook AI Research to EC2, Roblox to EKS, and Bloomberg to SageMaker.

Total Personalize NM (including Stark) is expected to reach breakeven NM% in 2026, even though on a standalone basis Personalize is expect to be \+13% NM in 2026\. This is mostly driven by Stark, which will launch in 2022\. As part of Stark PRFAQ process, we will refine the financials and propose optimizations to ensure that Total Personalize turns NM positive sooner.

# **Appendix F: Downstream Impact (DSI) Analysis of Selected AWS Artificial Intelligence (AI) Services**  {#appendix-f:-downstream-impact-(dsi)-analysis-of-selected-aws-artificial-intelligence-(ai)-services}

**The Ask.** The ACE-DSI team has been tasked with refreshing the DSI analysis of 10 services in the AI/ML suite: Rekognition,   Polly,   Lex,   SageMaker,   Comprehend,   Transcribe,   Translate,    Personalize,    Textract, and Comprehend Medical (henceforth Comprehend-M). These are *untailored* analyses, i.e. we do not employ domain knowledge to inform the design of the analysis.

**The Results of the 4th Round of DSI Analyses.** What Has Changed: Compared to our latest analyses (July 2020 and Sept 2020), we have: 1\) extended the data to May 2021; 2\) switched from EC2-BI to DBS-BI for AI metrics; and, 3\) standardized the analysis; specifically, now: a) we use a common post-adoption window of 6 months; b) we report the lift on spend on all AWS services, excluding only the service under analysis, e.g. the lift of SageMaker is the incremental non-SageMaker spend; and, c) we apply a top/bottom 2% trimming. Regarding item 3.a, recall that previously we used shorter windows for services that were too young to allow for a 6 months window. We now have enough post-launch months for all services to apply a common window. Regarding item 3.b, recall that previously, and for most AI services, the lift that we reported was the sum of those service-specific lifts that were statistically significant at the 5% level, i.e. those service-specific lifts that on statistical grounds we could tell apart from zero. By reporting the overall lift, we now follow a more statistically sound approach. Finally, regarding item 3.c, experience has shown that estimates can swing from refresh to refresh because of a few aberrant observations. We now better protect against such occurrences by trimming the sample. Taken together these changes align the DSI analyses of AI services with those of other services. What Has Stayed the Same: We employ the same estimation methodology used in the past. Consider for example SageMaker. We estimate the incremental spend from SageMaker, i.e. its **DSI Lift**, as the post-adoption difference in the average spend of SageMaker adopters and that of a curated group of non-adopters. The adopters of SageMaker are customers that spend at least $4 in a least a month on SageMaker, and keep their SageMaker spend positive for the subsequent 5 months. We choose the non-adopters so that their AWS spend grows at a similar *rate* as the adopters’ during the 6 months leading up to the adopters adopting SageMaker. (If there is a residual difference in the pre-adoption *level* of spend between the two groups, we net it out of the post-adoption difference.) We also continue to define SageMaker’s **DSI Multiplier** as its DSI Lift divided by SageMaker spend. This means that if SageMaker DSI Multiplier estimate is, say, $1.0, it means that every dollar spent on SageMaker is estimated to yield $1.0 of incremental spend towards other AWS services during the 6 months following SageMaker adoption. The Latest DSI Estimates: Table [1](#heading=h.28h4qwu) summarizes the DSI estimates obtained so far. The DSI estimates for Rekognition, SageMaker, and Comprehend Medical are all significantly different from zero at the 10% significance level (or lower): with confidence we can conclude that their true DSI Lift is positive (albeit with the usual caveats of every causal analysis). Conversely, we cannot rule out that the true DSI Lift for the other 7 services is zero. For them, a conservative approach uses 0.0 in place of the actual estimate when projecting DSI revenue. Here are a few more details:

Rekognition & Polly: Our previous analyses already employed a 6 months post-adoption window. Thus the differences in the estimates compared to July 2020 are driven by the added/new data, the fact that we no longer exclude AWS services not significantly impacted, and the trimming. 30% of the Rekognition DSI Lift is in the form of incremental spend on storage services. For Polly this percentage is 50% (but Polly overall lift is not statistically different from zero as mentioned above).

Lex, SageMaker, Comprehend, Transcribe, & Translate: Our previous analyses employed a post-adoption window shorter than 6 months. Thus the differences in the estimates are driven by the added/new data, the extended window, the fact that we no longer exclude AWS services not significantly impacted, and the trimming. 73% of the SageMaker DSI Lift is in the form of incremental spend on compute, analytics and database services. 27%, and respectively 46%, of the DSI Lift of Transcribe and Lex is in the form of incremental *Connect* spend (as mentioned above the overall lifts are not statistically different from zero). 30%, and respectively 36%, of the DSI Lift of Comprehend and Translate is in the form of incremental spend on other AI services (as mentioned the overall lifts are not statistically different from zero).

Personalize, Textract, & Comprehend-M Our previous analyses already employed the new design. Thus the differences in the estimates are driven by the added/new data. Of note, 24% of Comprehend-M lift is in the form of incremental spend on other AI services.

# **Appendix H: 2022 Languages Accuracy Benchmark Data** {#appendix-h:-2022-languages-accuracy-benchmark-data}

**Comprehend**  
In 2021, we evaluated Comprehend on entity type recognition, personal identifiable information (PII) redaction and sentiment scoring across 10 different languages. The first chart shows our performance against our key competitors Azure and GCP for entity type recognition and PII redaction. For entity recognition, scored was based the ability to detect and identify 13 distinct PII entity types (e.g., email, credit card number). For PII redaction, scoring was based on the ability to identify data as PII, regardless of if it detected the entity type correctly. F1 is an overall measure of a model’s accuracy that combines precision and recall together. An F1 score is considered perfect when it’s 1, while the model is a total failure when it’s 0\. Precision is the ability of the model to provide true positive results and recall is the sensitivity true positive results.

For both entity type recognition and PII redaction, AWS scored higher on both datasets compared to Azure and GCP. For the PII redaction test case, although everyone had higher scores compared to the entity type test case, AWS still had the highest score across both datasets. According to our knowledge, test results and reverse-engineering work, most PII entity recognition and redaction supported by Azure/GCP are powered by legacy techniques such as regex. Comprehend uses State of the Art ML (SoTA ML) algorithms such as neural networks which helps to explain why Azure/GCP performed poorly in this competitive benchmarking study that was based on complex datasets (heavily context-reliant data, spelled out entities, etc.).

**Kendra**   
The following tables list Kendra’s accuracy scores, broken down according to its three key models: Document Ranking (DR), Question Answering (QA) and FAQ Matching (FAQM). Document ranking sorts the documents and returns the most relevant documents for a given query. Question Answering attempts to answer a natural language question query by extracting a section of a document that directly contains the answer. FAQM returns the most relevant FAQ entry for a given query. Kendra models support English only today, with a plan to expand to at least two more in 2022\. 

We use different accuracy metrics for Document Ranking, Question Answering and FAQ Matching. For Document Ranking, the accuracy measure we use is Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain (NDCG). NDCG measures the relative relevance of each document based on its position in the ranked list, Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR) which measures the reciprocal of the rank of each correct answer, Precision (P) which measures the fraction of relevant documents among the retrieved document, and Recall (R) which measures the fraction of relevant documents among all relevant documents. These four metrics have values in the range of 0 and 1, with higher values indicating better accuracy.   For Question Answering task, we use Exact Match (EM). EM has values in the range of 0 and 100, with higher values indicating better accuracy. 

We measure the above metrics based on a combination of academic and customer datasets (e.g. Intuit, Internal Search, Pfizer, Sage).

![][image17]  
	  
For Document Ranking, Kendra underperforms the Reference (SOTA) on public benchmark datasets including Robust04 and MSMARCO. The main reasons for the gap are 1\) the SOTA uses methods optimized to perform well on the specific dataset while Kendra is optimized to perform well on a variety of datasets across domains. 2\) Kendra DR model only uses the top 3 passages per doc for document ranking due to latency constraints, whereas the reference model uses all passages. For Question Answering, Kendra underperforms the SOTA on TriviaQA and NQ. The main reason is that SOTA uses a combination of lexical and neural based document retrieval. Kendra will be supporting neural retrieval in 2022\.

**Lex**   
For Lex, we performed accuracy benchmarks against GCP’s Dialogflow and Nuance. 

**Dialogflow**: We conducted an end-to-end benchmarking (speech and text) against Google Dialogflow for the 10 Lex languages launched last year. We measured the performance (accuracy) on two metrics: (1) In domain (ID) Intent classification (IC) F1 is the ability to correctly classify an ID utterance to a correct intent. ID IC F1 is critical to deliver optimal performance in call routing use case and a score upwards of 70% is generally required by customers.   (2) Dependent slot labelling (SL) F1 is a measure of slot labeling performance. SL F1 is key for accurately capturing user information in a conversation. This score can vary depending on the type of information captured. For example, Numbers and Dates have a higher SL F1 score of 80-90% whereas first names, last names, email addresses are lower in 40-50% range. We are expanding to include built-ins performance by end of this year.

Based on our benchmarking results (Table 1 below), the median ID IC F1 score for Lex is 82.5% (range: 75-90%) and the median SL F1 score is 61% (range: 25-89%). Lex consistently outperforms Google Dialogflow across all languages on both metrics.  Languages such as German are inherently more complex and have lower accuracy scores compared to English and Spanish. Also, lack of conversational data in case of languages that are relatively spoken by a smaller population (e.g., French) can result in a lower accuracy score.

**Nuance:** We conducted an ASR benchmarking (speech only) against Nuance base models for US English. We measured performance on two metrics (1) Word error rate (WER): It represents the number of words incorrectly transcribed and is used as measure for transcription accuracy. (2) Content Word Error (CWER):  Content WER measures the transcription accuracy of subset of words that can impact the semantic meaning of the sentence in which they occur.

Based on our benchmarking results, we observed that Lex performs better compared to the Nuance base models. We did not benchmark against tuned Nuance grammars since any meaningful tuning can only be achieved over a period of time in a production environment. Also, we limited the benchmarking to US English and plan to expand coverage to other languages by end of year.

**Benchmarking plan:** We will take a tiered approach to establish performance targets for the languages planned over the next 2-3 years. We will categorize language into three tiers (tier 1, 2, and 3\) based on the language’s revenue potential, complexity and data availability. The revenue potential is determined based on the expected Connect pipeline for these languages. We work closely with the Connect GTM team to prioritize language expansion. Complexity is determined by the linguistic characteristics of a language. For example, the absence of short vowels in Arabic increases the language ambiguity. Complex languages require more effort in the form of higher number of iterations to train the ML models. Lastly, data availability is an important factor towards language delivery. We need conversational data to train and benchmark NLU, ASR, and built-ins on Lex. Languages spoken in North America and Western Europe have higher data availability.

The three language tiers based on these factors are: (1) **Tier 1**: Languages with high revenue potential, medium to high complexity and high data availability are categorized as tier 1\. This includes languages spoken in Americas and Western Europe along with Japanese and Korean. We can tune these languages to achieve an **ID IC F1 of 75-90%.** (2) **Tier 2:** Languages with medium revenue potential and high complexity are categorized as tier 2\. Some of these languages may not have data easily available. In this category we have Nordic languages (e.g., Norwegian, Swedish, Danish), APAC languages (e.g., Hindi, Cantonese, Thai), Middle East (e.g., Gulf Arabic) and African languages (e.g., Afrikaans). Given the complexity of these languages we are targeting **60-75% ID IC F1**. (3) **Tier 3**: languages that have relatively lower revenue potential but high complexity. Regional languages spoken in the Indian subcontinent (e.g., Bengali, Punjabi), Eastern European languages (e.g., Hungarian) and less spoken European languages (e.g., Slovenian, Valencian) are categorized as tier 3\. We will target **50-60% ID IC F1** given the high complexity and relatively low data availability. 

A summary of the criteria along with a comprehensive list of languages in each category is listed below:

**Amazon Translate**   
For Amazon Translate, we have both external and internal benchmark data. 

**External, third party benchmarking of Amazon Translate**  
Intento is one of the leading organizations helping global companies procure and utilize the best-fit cognitive AI services. In October 2021, Intento published an independent study that ranked Amazon Translate the best out of all the MT providers. Intento evaluated 15 of the most prominent MT providers used by language service providers and localization services. The data used included examples from across 16 industry sectors, with 8 content types, including topics such as financial documentation, patents, sales and marketing material. These inputs were translated between 14 common language pairs to determine the best engine for a given translation scenario. It ranked the results of each MT engine based on how they compared to a reference human translation. The results showed that no MT service is best in all language pairs across all industry sectors and content types. However, Amazon Translate had the highest number of instances in which it was rated “best.”

![][image20]

**Internal benchmarking of Amazon Translate**  
Internal benchmarking of Amazon Translate is done on a bi-monthly basis. The team uses “blind sets” with Amazon Translate, Google, and Bing and send them for human evaluation. If the arc number is 100% or above, that indicates Amazon Translate is better. If the number is 80-100%, this means the services are on par compared to each other. In summary, Amazon Translate is on par with Google and slightly ahead of Microsoft. Unlike the evaluation studies for other language services, translation does not have a ground truth because content can be translated “correctly” in a number of ways. As a result, this study is not a definitive reflection of how our customers perceive our quality and should be utilized in conjunction with other evaluations like the external one from Intento. In addition, we have not lost any POCs in a bake-off situation which often focuses on translation accuracy.
